'''Brian D. Unger'''<ref name="Ohio Birth Index">{{cite web|title=Ohio Birth Index|url=http://www.ogs.org/research/results_ohbirths.php|publisher=Ogs.org|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> (born July 12, 1965)<ref name="Brian Unger Twitter">{{cite web|title=Brian Unger Twitter|url=http://twitter.com/bungerla|publisher=Twitter.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] actor, comedian, writer, producer, and commentator.

==Biography==
Born in [[Dayton, Ohio]] to Richard ("Rich") Unger and Eleanor ("Ellie") Oprea, Unger grew up in [[Granville, Ohio|Granville]]. He graduated from [[Ohio University]] in 1987, where he majored in [[communication studies|communication]].<ref name=ohio>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=2681|title=Brian Unger|work=Ohio History Central|publisher=Ohio Historical Society|date=August 1, 2006}}</ref>  He had worked on a television show called ''Fridays Live'', an OU student-produced comedy show airing on [[WOUB-TV]], the local PBS affiliate.  Unger recently returned to make a cameo on the show's Season 17 finale. Unger has [[Romanians|Romanian]] ethnic heritage.<ref>on his own admission at minute 98 of the ''[[How the States Got Their Shapes]]'' special</ref>

==The Daily Show==
Unger was an original correspondent and producer on ''[[The Daily Show]]'', from 1996-99. <ref name="Yahoo TV">{{cite web|title=Yahoo TV|url=http://tv.yahoo.com/brian-unger/contributor/1035452|publisher=Tv.yahoo.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> While working for ''[[The Daily Show]]'' in 1998, he was named one of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s "100 Most Creative People in Entertainment." <ref name=ohio/> Unger's other [[television]] appearances include ''[[O2Be]]'' on [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]], the [[Comedy Central]] shows ''[[Reno 911!]]'' and ''[[The Man Show]]'', various [[I Love...|''I Love the...'']] shows on [[VH1]], ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]],'' ''Hollywood Off-Ramp'' on [[E!]], as well as appearances on NBC's ''[[The Jay Leno Show]]'' and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', [[NBC]]'s ''[[Later (talk show)|Later]]'', [[E!]]'s ''[[Talk Soup]],'' the syndicated entertainment newsmagazine ''[[Extra (TV program)|Extra]]'', the stand-up comedy [[DVD]] ''[[Zach Galifianakis Live at the Purple Onion]]''.

He provided regular commentary ("The Unger Report") for the [[NPR]] show ''[[Day to Day]]'' from its launch in 2003 until its cancellation, making his final "Unger Report" on March 16, 2009.  He currently provides regular commentary to NPR's ''[[All Things Considered]]''.

He has hosted on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'' and [[Discovery Channel]] show ''[[Some Assembly Required (TV series)|Some Assembly Required]]'' (with University of Virginia Professor of Physics Lou Bloomfield; and then solo in its final season).  Unger was one of the co-hosts for the pilot of a new PBS series, ''[[Wired Science]]'', which aired in January 2007 and was subsequently picked up to debut later in the year, though Unger did not remain involved with the show.<ref>[http://www.pbs.org/kcet/wiredscience/page/credits_prod.html] {{dead link|date=October 2014}}</ref>

Unger has appeared as a spokesman for [[Yoo-hoo]] and [[Maxwell House]] Coffee. In 2008, he appeared in a BMW documentary about testing of BMW diesels as they embark on a 500-mile road trip from South Carolina to Virginia. The film's purpose was to raise awareness of driving diesels in the United States. Unger later became the official spokesman for the BMW Advanced Diesel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brandchannel.com/home/post/2009/09/23/Minor-Celeb-Endorsements-Trip-Up-Sony-BMW.aspx|title=Minor Celeb Endorsements Trip Up Sony, BMW|author=Abe Sauer|publisher=Brandchannel.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> He also appears in a number of recent [[Quicken Loans]] commercials.

Unger's written commentary has appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''The Minneapolis [[Star Tribune]]'', and he has written a  book review for ''[[The Washington Post]]''. He is a commentator on the internet talk show ''[[The Young Turks]]'', which streams on YouTube; it is one of the most watched news programs produced solely for the web. The show shortly joined the former [[Current TV]] television network from 2011 to 2013.

==How the States Got Their Shapes==
Unger hosted a documentary special on [[History (TV channel)|The History Channel]] titled ''[[How the States Got Their Shapes]]''.  In 2011, the network expanded the special into a weekly series, which Unger hosts. As of 2014, Unger co-hosts ''Showdown of the Unbeatables''.

As of September 8, 2013, Brian Unger hosted an NFL.com segment titled "Game Day Satisfaction: Week 1".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-super-bowl/0ap2000000240934/Game-Day-Satisfaction-Week-1|title=Game Day Satisfaction: Week 1|work=NFL.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>

